The frequency of any standing‐wave mode in a wind instrument is proportional to the speed of sound, and  
\[v\propto\sqrt{T_{\rm abs}}\,,\]  
where \(T_{\rm abs}\) is the temperature in kelvins.  Hence  
\[\frac{f_{30}}{f_{10}}=\frac{v_{30}}{v_{10}}
=\sqrt{\frac{T_{30}}{T_{10}}}
=\sqrt{\frac{273.15+30.0}{273.15+10.0}}
=\sqrt{\frac{303.15}{283.15}}\approx1.035\,. \]  
So the frequencies at 30 °C are about 3.5% higher than at 10 °C.
